# 35_objects_path_data — opens the canvas-observable scripts arc.
#
# s235 m1 wired the canvas-refresh callback into ObjectsScriptable's
# every mutating verb, but the smoke for that wiring couldn't be
# canvas-observable: the only verbs that touched scene-objects (new,
# delete, toggle_visible, etc.) didn't produce pixels on canvas. A
# minted Path with empty path data renders nothing; toggling visible
# on a Path with no geometry is invisible. The s235 close logged a
# direct gap: scripts can't BUILD UP canvas-observable targets.
#
# s236 m1 closes the first piece of that gap by adding `set_path_data
# <svg_d_string>` to the ObjectProxy. The verb takes an SVG-d
# attribute string, parses it through curvz_utils' new path-d pump,
# and pushes EditPathCommand (the s167/s168-migrated whole-path
# replace command — already iid-shaped, perfect fit; no parallel
# command class needed, unlike m3's EditObjectFieldCommand or m4's
# MoveNodeIndexCommand). Fill / stroke / actual canvas-visible
# rendering land in subsequent milestones; m1 ships geometry, which
# is the foundation — fill on an empty Path still draws nothing.
#
# s237 m1 retrofits set_path_data and path_data to interpret coords
# in user-space (Y-up, origin at bottom-left of artboard) rather
# than doc-space (Y-down, top-left). The d-string the user types
# is parsed into PathData, then flipped through CoordSpace (the
# canonical Y-flip seam in include/CoordSpace.hpp) before being
# stored as doc-space PathData. On the read side, path_data flips
# the stored doc-space PathData back to user-space before emitting.
# Users see geometry land where their rulers say it should land.
#
# Phase 4 reads "M 0 0 L 100 0 L 100 100 L 0 100 Z" as a 100×100
# rect anchored at the bottom-left of the page — where Y=0 means
# the page floor. The visual channel: the rect lives at user-origin
# (where a ruler typed (0, 0) would point), not at doc-origin
# (top-left, where s236 m1's rect landed). The trace channel: the
# rect still has 4 BezierNodes, the triangle still has 3 — the
# Y-flip is structure-preserving by construction (each BezierNode
# flips its anchor + both handles; no nodes added or dropped).
#
# The smoke also exercises the new `node_count` proxy query (the
# observable for `set_path_data`'s effect — integer, deterministic,
# no Cairo) and the read-side `path_data` query (round-trip view of
# the d-string back from the model; trace-channel only, the
# normalised re-emission isn't byte-identical to the input so no
# literal-RHS assert is shippable).
#
# ── Owns-its-conditions structure (CANON) ────────────────────────────────
#
# BUILD UP / VALIDATE / TEAR DOWN. The smoke mints its own test
# layer and test objects, validates the new surface end-to-end,
# and tears everything back down. Net structural change to the
# doc: zero. Side effect on the undo stack: AddNodeCommand for the
# mints, EditPathCommand entries for the set_path_data calls,
# DeleteObjectCommand pairs for the teardown.
#
# ── Pre-stated count ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Expected: 10 pass / 0 fail / 0 error.
#
# Breakdown:
#   Phase 3 (BUILD UP — mint `p` as Path, baseline shape):
#     type == "path", node_count == 0                         → 2 asserts.
#   Phase 4 (SET — closed rect, 4 BezierNodes):
#     node_count == 4                                          → 1 assert.
#   Phase 5 (CHANGE — closed triangle, 3 BezierNodes):
#     node_count == 3                                          → 1 assert.
#   Phase 6 (PATH_DATA query — bind + visual, trace-channel only):
#                                                              → 0 asserts.
#   Phase 7 (CLEAR — empty d-string, 0 BezierNodes):
#     node_count == 0                                          → 1 assert.
#   Phase 8 (OPEN PATH — no Z terminator, 3 BezierNodes):
#     node_count == 3                                          → 1 assert.
#   Phase 9 (NEGATIVE — set_path_data on a Group is a no-op):
#     g type == "group", g node_count == 0                     → 2 asserts.
#   Phase 10 (CROSS-CHECK — find_by_type "path" finds `p`):
#     found_path type == "path"                                → 1 assert.
#   Phase 11 (TEAR DOWN — round-trip count):
#     objects count == count_before                            → 1 assert.
#
# Total: 2 + 1 + 1 + 0 + 1 + 1 + 2 + 1 + 1 = 10.
#
# (s237 m1 originally added a Phase 6b — feed the captured path_data
# d-string back through set_path_data and assert node_count survives
# the round-trip. The DSL splits text-valued variables on whitespace
# when they appear in verb-arg position, so `set_path_data pd_out`
# tokenises as ten args instead of one; arg_as_string(args[0]) picks
# up just "M" and the parser returns a one-anchor PathData. The bug
# is in the DSL's variable-substitution shape, not in the pump pair.
# Logged on the backlog as "DSL: text variables in verb-arg position
# need single-token treatment." The user-space round-trip itself IS
# observable through the convergence of Phase 6's clean re-emission
# and Phases 4/5/7/8's literal-RHS asserts on user-space coords — the
# Phase 6b structural-survival probe was nice-to-have, not load-
# bearing. A future DSL milestone will bring back a real assert.)
#
# ── On the `node_count` observable ───────────────────────────────────────
#
# `node_count` returns the size of the Path's BezierNode vector — a
# pure model-side property, no Cairo, no rendering, deterministic
# across runs. After `set_path_data "M 0 0 L 100 0 L 100 100 L 0 100
# Z"` the value is 4 (one BezierNode per anchor; Z closes the path
# without adding a node). After `set_path_data ""` the value is 0.
# After `set_path_data "M 0 0 L 50 50 L 100 0"` (open path, no Z)
# the value is 3.
#
# For non-Path nodes (Group / Compound / Image / etc.), path_data
# isn't a meaningful concept (path == nullptr), so node_count
# degrades to 0 — matching the "node_count is the size of nodes,
# treating a missing path as having no nodes" contract documented
# on the query.
#
# Bbox queries (bbox_w / bbox_h) would be the natural follow-on
# observable for true canvas-coverage validation, but bbox math
# requires the Cairo pass and isn't pure-model. Scheduled for a
# later milestone if a smoke needs it. node_count is sufficient
# for the round-trip "did set_path_data land in the model?" check.
#
# ── On the `path_data` read-side query ───────────────────────────────────
#
# Returns the SVG-d string representation of the Path's PathData,
# re-emitted via the same `path_data_to_svg_d` pump SvgWriter uses
# (after the s236 m1 pump promotion). The emitter normalises the
# input (lossless on the model layer, but textually different —
# "M 0 0" becomes "M 0.00 0.00" with fmt2 formatting, segments
# always emit as C or L depending on handle degeneracy, etc.). So
# the round-trip isn't byte-identical and a literal-RHS assert
# would be brittle.
#
# The query is exposed anyway because scripts that want to capture
# geometry need the read side, and because the trace shows whether
# the round-trip preserves the structural shape (same number of
# anchors, same closed/open status). Phase 6 binds the result to
# a variable and lets the trace carry the value for human
# inspection.
#
# ── Canvas-observable (three-channel acceptance) ─────────────────────────
#
# Trace channel: the 10 asserts above.
# Visual channel: the test path is minted under a test layer that
#   the user can see in the Layers panel. After Phase 4's SET, the
#   path has rect geometry but no fill / stroke (m1 doesn't ship
#   appearance verbs), so it renders as an outline-only rect in
#   wireframe mode — or as nothing in fill-only modes. m2's
#   `set_fill` makes the rect canvas-visible in all modes. For m1,
#   a useful visual probe is running with Canvas in node/outline
#   mode and watching the rect appear / change / disappear across
#   phases.
# Build channel: Scott's compile.
#
# Phase 9's negative case (set_path_data on a Group) is a no-op
# without an error sentinel — the verb body resolves the node,
# checks node->path is non-null, and silently early-returns when
# it isn't. That's the same shape every other proxy verb uses for
# refused arg-class cases (no error reporting through ScriptValue;
# the trace just shows the verb dispatched without effect). Future
# milestones may add a structured error channel; m1 inherits the
# convention.

#[sub] === Phase 1: REGISTRY ===
#[sub] `objects` should appear in the registry list — same baseline
#[sub] check smoke 34 opens with.

list

#[sub] === Phase 2: DISPATCH — baseline count ===
#[sub] Captures the pre-mint count to compare against after teardown.

get objects count
set count_before to result

#[sub] === Phase 3: BUILD UP — mint test layer and Path object ===
#[sub] Same shape as smoke 34: mint a sentinel-named test layer,
#[sub] activate it, then mint `p` under it via `objects new "path"`.
#[sub] A freshly-minted Path has empty PathData (the documented
#[sub] contract — see ObjectsScriptable header). node_count returns
#[sub] 0 against an empty path's nodes vector.

layers new
set test_layer to result
layers.test_layer rename "objects_path_data_smoke_s236_m1"
layers.test_layer activate

objects new "path"
set p to result

assert objects.p type == "path"
assert objects.p node_count == 0

#[sub] === Phase 4: SET — closed rect (4 anchors, Z terminator) ===
#[sub] Canonical 100×100 rect at the origin. Four BezierNodes (one
#[sub] per corner); the Z terminator closes the path without adding
#[sub] a node. set_path_data parses the d-string through curvz_utils'
#[sub] svg_d_to_path_data pump, captures the existing PathData as
#[sub] `before`, replaces it with the parsed value, and pushes
#[sub] EditPathCommand for undo.

objects.p set_path_data "M 0 0 L 100 0 L 100 100 L 0 100 Z"
assert objects.p node_count == 4

#[sub] === Phase 5: CHANGE — closed triangle (3 anchors) ===
#[sub] Replaces the rect's PathData with a triangle. EditPathCommand
#[sub] captures rect-PathData as `before` and triangle-PathData as
#[sub] `after`; Ctrl+Z then restores the rect. The smoke doesn't
#[sub] exercise undo (visual-channel concern for Scott's three-
#[sub] channel acceptance, not script-channel coverage).

objects.p set_path_data "M 0 0 L 100 0 L 50 100 Z"
assert objects.p node_count == 3

#[sub] === Phase 6: PATH_DATA QUERY — read-side round-trip ===
#[sub] Bind the re-emitted d-string to a variable. The trace shows
#[sub] the value; no literal-RHS assert because the re-emission is
#[sub] normalised (fmt2 formatting, L-vs-C segment classification),
#[sub] so byte-equality with the original input isn't a stable
#[sub] property. A future round-trip-fidelity probe would parse
#[sub] both strings to PathData and compare structurally; the DSL
#[sub] doesn't carry that compare shape today.
#[sub]
#[sub] s237 m1: the emitted d-string is in user-space — same Y-up
#[sub] frame the original input used. The convergence of this
#[sub] phase's trace output (user-space coords in the d-string)
#[sub] and Phases 4/5/7/8's literal-RHS asserts (user-space coords
#[sub] in the inputs) is the user-space round-trip probe. A real
#[sub] re-set-from-captured-string assert needs the DSL to treat
#[sub] text variables as single tokens in verb-arg position; logged
#[sub] on the backlog.

get objects.p path_data
set pd_out to result

#[sub] === Phase 7: CLEAR — empty d-string ===
#[sub] set_path_data "" replaces the triangle's PathData with an
#[sub] empty one. The parser returns an empty PathData for empty
#[sub] input (the same shape `objects new "path"` produces). Useful
#[sub] as a clearing primitive without deleting the node.

objects.p set_path_data ""
assert objects.p node_count == 0

#[sub] === Phase 8: OPEN PATH — no Z terminator ===
#[sub] M + 2 L segments, no Z. Three BezierNodes; closed == false
#[sub] in the resulting PathData. The model represents open and
#[sub] closed paths with the same BezierNode vector and a separate
#[sub] `closed` bool, so node_count is the same shape regardless.
#[sub] (A future `closed` query would be the natural pair to
#[sub] distinguish the two; not in m1 scope.)

objects.p set_path_data "M 0 0 L 50 50 L 100 0"
assert objects.p node_count == 3

#[sub] === Phase 9: NEGATIVE — set_path_data on a Group is a no-op ===
#[sub] Mint a Group; Groups don't carry a PathData (path == nullptr
#[sub] on every non-Path node). set_path_data on the group's proxy
#[sub] should resolve the node, check `node->path`, see it's null,
#[sub] and silently early-return without pushing a command.
#[sub] node_count on a Group degrades to 0 (no nodes vector to
#[sub] size; treated as 0 by contract). type round-trips as "group".

objects new "group"
set g to result

assert objects.g type == "group"
assert objects.g node_count == 0

objects.g set_path_data "M 0 0 L 100 100 Z"

#[sub] === Phase 10: CROSS-CHECK — find_by_type now resolves ===
#[sub] With `p` in scope (and `g`), find_by_type "path" should
#[sub] return a path-typed iid. We assert on type, not on iid
#[sub] identity, because find_by_type's "first hit" contract
#[sub] doesn't guarantee which path it returns when more than one
#[sub] is in scope (and there may be user-drawn paths in the doc
#[sub] from before the script ran).

objects find_by_type "path"
set found_path to result
assert objects.found_path type == "path"

#[sub] === Phase 11: TEAR DOWN ===
#[sub] Three mints (test_layer via layers.new, p via objects.new,
#[sub] g via objects.new) need three matching deletes. The Path
#[sub] gets its PathData freed when DeleteObjectCommand owns the
#[sub] snapshot; no leak. count returns to count_before — round-
#[sub] trip baseline.

objects delete p
objects delete g
layers delete test_layer

get objects count
assert objects count == count_before

#[sub] === Final list — registry sanity ===
#[sub] Same shape as smoke 34's close: `objects` still present, no
#[sub] transient proxies registered, the dozens of proxy
#[sub] materialisations across this run all cleaned up at end-of-
#[sub] statement.

list

#[sub] Done. The s236 m1 + s237 m1 surface is validated:
#[sub]   - `objects.<iid> set_path_data <svg_d_string>` lands geometry
#[sub]     into the Path's PathData via curvz_utils' new
#[sub]     svg_d_to_path_data pump, flips parsed user-space PathData
#[sub]     to doc-space via the s237 m1 path_data_user_to_doc pump,
#[sub]     pushes EditPathCommand for undo, fires the s235 m1
#[sub]     canvas-refresh callback at success.
#[sub]   - Empty d-string clears the path (node_count → 0).
#[sub]   - Open paths (no Z) round-trip with node_count matching
#[sub]     the anchor count.
#[sub]   - set_path_data on non-Path nodes (Group) is a clean no-op.
#[sub]   - `node_count` read query gives scripts an observable for
#[sub]     geometry changes — integer, deterministic, no Cairo.
#[sub]   - `path_data` read query gives scripts the d-string round-
#[sub]     trip for capture / inspection use cases (trace-channel
#[sub]     observable, not literal-RHS-assertable due to fmt2
#[sub]     normalisation). Returns user-space coords as of s237 m1 —
#[sub]     Phase 6's trace output converges with Phases 4/5/7/8's
#[sub]     literal-RHS asserts to validate the user-space round-trip
#[sub]     without a separate re-set-from-captured-string phase.
#[sub]
#[sub] Pre-stated: 10 pass / 0 fail / 0 error.
#[sub]
#[sub] What's still NOT covered by m1 (and that's by design):
#[sub]   - `set_fill` / `set_stroke`. Scheduled m2 / m3. Without
#[sub]     those, the rect / triangle / open-path are wireframe-
#[sub]     only on canvas.
#[sub]   - `bbox_w` / `bbox_h` queries. Bbox needs the Cairo path
#[sub]     pass; non-trivial. Future milestone if a smoke needs it.
#[sub]   - `closed` query (the bool flag on PathData). Useful pair
#[sub]     to node_count for round-tripping shape; future milestone.
#[sub]   - `require <var>` flow-control verb (logged backlog from
#[sub]     s235). Phase 6's `set pd_out to result` would benefit
#[sub]     from a "did the prior step produce something?" gate; for
#[sub]     m1 the smoke runs unconditionally because Phase 5's
#[sub]     SET is the precondition and we trust it landed (the
#[sub]     assert in Phase 5 IS the gate).
#[sub]   - Byte-identical round-trip of the d-string. Re-emission
#[sub]     normalises whitespace and segment-type classification;
#[sub]     a structural round-trip probe (parse out, parse in,
#[sub]     compare PathData) needs a DSL extension not in m1 scope.
#[sub]   - Visual centering. The user-space-flipped geometry lands
#[sub]     at the bottom-left of the page (user-origin) rather than
#[sub]     centered. A future milestone may add a `proj` singleton
#[sub]     with page-width/height queries so smokes can mint geometry
#[sub]     centered without hardcoded coords; for now, near-the-
#[sub]     origin geometry is the convention.
